espect and gives silence back in return, while the Drum keeps its slow measure. In the hush after, Aerin wades to the tall reeds that grow on the mound's leeward side, cuts a length of heart-reed that vibrates to the hidden thrum, and threads it with her breathing as the rite requires, each exhale catching a strand of that old, kind tone. The reed warms in her palm like a pulse and holds a sound that could quiet a crowd at the edge of stampede or coax a shivering rib to stillness, a borrowed heartbeat sealed in a hollow stem.\",\n      \"objectives\": [\n        \"Navigate the marsh channels safely to the Drum of Reeds and withstand will-o’-wisps’ lures.\",\n        \"Confront Roa Mestri and secure her sworn confession for the Vigil.\",\n        \"Repel the eel-skin hireblades and identify Rafter-style knots among their gear.\",\n        \"Harvest a length of heart-reed and bind it with Breathkeeper rite to capture the heart-tone.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Roa Mestri\", \"lines\": \"I thought one bell would calm the stampede, and I told myself that a slower breath would save more than it would risk. I thought I could hold the storm in my mouth like a prayer-stone, that the wind would wait for my hands to finish tallying and the city would thank me for my patience. Ulo's coin felt like a weight I could set down later, just a token pressed into my palm until the next tide brought better choices, but it settled into my pocket like silt and would not come out. Forgive me if you can, because I am not sure I can forgive myself, and I am tired of tasting copper every time I hear the horn. I will go to the Oathwater and I will not lie, and if the Vigil must bind me in chains then let them, but let the chains be honest ones and not made of my excuses.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Aerin Rell\", \"lines\": \"Confess and stand straight, Roa Mestri, because a bent back makes a crooked oath and we both have had enough of those. The breath is not 