d and the quiet that follows a job done, and there are more of us in the cattails than minutes in your next prayer. Think on how fast the marsh swallows a body and how slow the Vigil climbs ladders when night falls, and weigh that against the clever little vows you keep behind your teeth. Be wise like the river and bend, because the straight tree is the first to snap when the gale comes screaming down the ravine.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Aerin Rell\", \"lines\": \"The only thing I will leave in these reeds is your threat, and even that the marsh will chew into something soft and harmless if it has the time. The mud takes what is thrown in anger and gives it back as stillness, and I have no intention of feeding it my oath or my companion. You speak of coin as if it is the only current worth riding, but I have heard bones sing and I know a deeper music that will not be bought with eel-skin silver. Step back and unstring your knots, because I see the Rafter way in them and I will remember each twist when I speak to the Vigil, and the Vigil will remember me. If you come on, I will break your breath and bless it in the same motion, and the Drum will beat over you like rain on a roof that you will never see again.\"}\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"C1\", \"title\": \"Escort Roa to Spinegate Hall under Vigil light\", \"text\": \"You lash the flatboat to a willow shank and raise your moonshard lantern in a Vigil pattern, calling lamplighters and wardens to meet you at Riverfoot as witnesses. You bind Roa's wrists with a prayer-knot she consents to wear, and you rehearse her full confession aloud until the fear leaves her tongue and only the facts remain. You collect one hireblade's knotted cord as evidence, noting the Rafter-style hitches and the smell of tar that clings like guilt. You refuse to chase rumors in the marsh's dark and choose instead the hard corridors of law, because swifter paths have already cost lives. You promise Roa that you will 